{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_fluorite_ver01/data/sn84020097/00332897664/1930120201/0586.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nMobilize at Central Opera House Tomorrow Night; Fight Against Injunctions!\nTWO MEETINGS PREPARE FURTHER\nBATTLE UPON VICIOUS INJUNCTIONS\nWorkers Greet Two Fighters Just Out of Jail\nat Banquet Tonight; Mass Mobilization\nat Central Opera House Tomorrow\nNEW YORK.\u2014Two preliminary\nmass gatherings to the next mass\nviolation of the injunction will be\nheld here. One is the great mass\nmeeting to mobilize to Smash the\nInjunction, called by the Trade\nUnion Unity Council and the Inter\nnational Labor Defense. All mili\ntant workers of New York and all\njobless are urged to gather at Cen\ntral Opera House, 67th St. and Third\nAve\u201e tomorrow night as a mobiliza\ntion for mass picketing in defiance\nof the strike-breaking injunctions.\nThe other preliminary gathering of\nthese who are determined to win\nback the right to strike and to picket\nis the banquet to greet Harry Cor\nnelius and Steve Stevenson, just re\nleased from serving a year and a\nhalf in prison for violating an in\njunction in the cafeteria strike. The\nbanquet will be held at Manhattan\nLyceum at 7:30 p. m. tonight. The\ntwo workers are enthusiastic about\nthe present fight, and show in their\nunterrified speeches and their deter\nmination that the bosses\u2019 jail did not\nfrighten them away from the class\nstruggle. They urge all fellow-work\ners to carry on the battle. All work\ners, of every trade and industry, j\nshould be at Manhattan Lyceum to\nnight to greet these heroic fighters.\nTickets are 50 cents and all funds\ngo to the fight against injunctions.\nFoster Urges AU to Come.\nAmong the speakers at Central Op\nera House mass meeting tomorrow\nnight will be Fred Biedenkapp. chair\nman of the Smash the Injunctions\nCommittee of the T. U. U. C.; J. Louis\nEngdahl, of the International Labor\nDefense, which defends the arrested\npickets; Jack Johnstone, organiser of\nMUSTE FAKERS OFFER PROGRAM OF\nEXTRFME INACTION FOR THE JOBLESS\nThe League For Industrial Democ-\nracy (Musteite Control) publishes a 1\nmagazine called \u201cThe Unemployed.\"\nIt has in its first issue a serious of\narticles from various shining lights\nof the exalted professions: three 1\npreachers, a profesor or two, an editor\nfor the Peabody Coal Co., and Hey\nwood Broun.\nBroun\u2019s articles leads. It tells of\nthe \"floater\u201d, who wouldn't work that\nBroun found on a breadline once. The\npoint of the whole article is that if\nbreadlines go on, the worker will begin\nto like them and no worker will work.\n\"I think it would be a swell stunt to\ncome along and save them before they\ntake the dive (into the breadline).\nSmart for you and me, I mean. After\nall, breadlines make breadliners\u201d. That\nis what Broun is worrying about,\nNorman Thomas is next with pure\nsocial fascism. He analyzes very cor\nrectly the couses of unemployment.\nThat's the radical phraseology. He\nsays nothing about direct struggle of\nthe jobless for insurance nor of the\nworkers against the things that in\ncrease unemployment. He just tells\nthem the only way out is to vote for\nhis gang. And that's the fascist part.\nReal Fascism\nBut if the Rev. Thomas is a social\nfascist, he is followed immediately by\na proposal for straight fascism. It\nis signed by Paul Blanschard. It is\nfor no overthrow of capitalism, but\njust for a state planning board which\nwould guarantee profits and a minim\num subsistence for the workers by re\ngulation of industry.\nThis regulation is called \u201ccomplete\nreconstruction of our social system\u201d\nand its form and methods can be seen\nin a couple of quotations from the\narticle:\n\"Under such a board no man would\nbe allowed to build a shoe factory\nwhen there were too many shoe fac\ntories already. No man would be per\nmitted to gamble with the jobs of\nthousands of workers unless he de\nmonstrated his ability to keep his fac\ntory running.\u201d\n\u201cIt may be objected that in such\na world there would be less freedom\nfor those who own and manipulate\nSPEED UP PAMPHLET REVEALS\nCAUSES OF UNEMPLOYMENT\nNEW YORK.\u2014Ten million unem\nployed workers standing in bread\nlines and sleeping in the open or in\nvermin-infested \u201ccharity\" beds are\nasking just what effect the return of\n\u201cprosperity\u201d confidently promised\nby the capitalist press at any time\nwithin the next few years\u2014w\u2019ill have\non them. The question is clearly\nand graphically answered in the\npamphlet \u201cSpeeding Up the Work\ners,\" by James Barnett, just issued\nby International Pamphlets. Here it\nis made plain that, so far as the\nworker is concerned, \u201cgood\" timc\\\nare hard times, and \u201cbad\" times are\nmerely worse times. Since the end\nof the latest imperialist war the\nnumber of workers employed in in\ndustry has steadily decreased. Dur\ning the period of capitalist \u201cprosper\nity\" which preceded the present crisis\n2.5 to 4 million workers were per\nmanently unemployed, with the num\nber constantly growing yid the in\nthe Trade Union Unity Council, and\nWilliam Z. Foster, general secretary\nof the Trade Union Unity League.\nThe enlarged national committee\nof the T. U. U. L., in its final session\nSaturday, adopted a resolution for\ncontinued fight against the injunc\ntion. after which Foster made the\nfollowing statement:\n\u201cThe struggle against the injunc\ntion weapon used by the bosses, by\nthe reactionary officials of the A. F.\nof L. and of the socialist party, is\nj one of the major struggles before\nthe American working class, involv\ni ing. as it does, the fundamental right\nj of workers to organize into militant\nfighting industrial unions and to\nj wrest from the employers by the\nweapons of strike and picket line\nbetter conditions.\n\u201cThe struggle to smash the in\njunction at Zelgreen Cafeteria is a\nstrike of the workers to smash the\n12-hour day put into effect by the\nA. F. of L. and the employers through\nthe use of injunctions, gangsters, po\nlice and courts. The only method of\nsmashing injunctions is to mobilize\nlarge masses of workers on the picket\nline to defy the orders of the court\nand to violate the injunction en\nmasse.\n\u201cWhether the struggle confronts\nthe food. shoe, needle or miners'\nunion, it becomes the struggle of the\nwhole working class.\n\u201cThe mass meeting called by the\nSmash the Injunction Committee of\nthe Trade Union Unity Council on\nWednesday, Dec. 3, in Central Opera\nHouse must rally thousands of work\ners and be a powerful expression of\nthe solidarity of the workers in the\nfight to smash the injunctions.\nindustry.\u201d\nBut they are to keep right on owing i\nindustry and collecting profits, though\nwise masters like Hittler and Mus-1\nsolini or perhaps Blanchard, will tell\nthem how, so they don't wreak things\nthrough too much individualism.\nThat's fascism, not social fascism, but\nplain fascism.\nA Sermon\u2019 200\nRev. Harry Emerson Fosdick prints\npart of a sermon appealing to big\nbusiness men in his Riverside church,\nasking them to please do something.\nBarry W. Laidler says there must\nbe at least 5,000,000 jobless, when even j\nthe director of the census admits there\nare about 9,000,000.\nOscar Ameringer, editor of the i\nAmerican (formerly Illinois) Miner, j\norgan of the \u201cReorganized United\nMine Workers,\u201d the pet union of the\nPeabody Coal Co., has an article. He\nwaxes jovial over the fact that a crip\npled apple seller sells better than a\nwhole apple seller. Oscar can aford\nsome humor, he used to get $72,000\na year for printing the Illinois Miner,\nno one knows what he gets now, he\nowns a large part of a printing plant\nand lots of real estate.\nAn editorial in the back is entitled\n\u201cPush Public Works\" and is nothing\nbut an argument for the Hoover build\ning program, which is already a flop.\nThe preacher who writes the very\nlast article in the magazine, a fellow\nnamed Lathrop. makes to the jobless\nthe one single suggestion of struggle\nin the whole thirty ne pages. He\nsays, the jobless might organize to\nforce the government to grant un\ni employment insurance. The last pa\nragraph of his article however, seems\nto indicate that all he means is that\nthey should join the socialist party or\nsome \u201cLabor Party\" to be sprung on\nj them by Normie and Blanchard.\nAgainst this misleadership the job\nj less are begining to mobilize in the\nCouncils of the Unemployed, to de\ni monstrate for immidiate relief, tc\ni militantly resist evictions, and to unite\ni with workers on the jobs to secure\ni shorter hours, more pay and fight\nj speed-up.\ndividual as well as the collective\nshare of the working class in indus\ntry becoming less and less.\nThe reason, Comrade Barnett\nmakes it clear, is in the speed-up\u2014\nthe technique of driving workers to\nthe limit of their endurance and\nforcing one man to do the work of\nmany with no increase in pay or\nshortening of hours. Capitalist\napologists attempt to disguise the\nspeed-up under the names of \u201ceffi\nciency\u201d or \u201crationalization.\u201d But\n\u201cSpeeding Up the Workers\u201d reveals\nthat there has been little technolo\ngical advance during the past dec\nade. Increased production is being\ntaken out of the nerves and muscles\nof workers who are then thrown on\nthe scrap heap or left to stand at the\nfactory gates as a threat to their al\nmost exhausted fellow workers in\nside.\nEvery worker, unemployed or still\nemployed, should read \u201cSpeeding Up\nTHE ADVENTURES OF BILL WORKER \u2014No Charity\u2014Unemployment Insurance\u2014 B AN W A L\nru cwt 'fte\nbiwefL -ABowl OF Joup Wirrt cwtfif/w 'Uj-AU p/2 \u00a3t N rfi\u00a3 MTH Mt NoW I Wa/nT l Fo<?0\n[Top MAA/Y fIeAN/ /HAKt'fou KiiAvoy That bUrJSiA'iq ON oup 1 r\\ \u00a3e -T QTI/tf Mr *-r J _ jjJ\nAMD Aatc\u00df THfcrfSwe A W C,T 4J A*P PoTaTOC'/\nAFL LAUNDRY RACKET\nMEANS LOWEST WACES\nNEW YORK\u2014Drivers' Local 810\nj of the A. F. of L. has gone in the\nI laundry business. The officials of,\nthe local have signed an agreement\nj with the Nonpareil Laundry. 546 E. j\n170th St., and promised the boss that\nthey will get him more business. The i\nofficials received the membership j\nlists of other A. F. of L. unions, such j\nas the Bakers, Barbers, etc., and j\nturned these over to the boss. All j\nwere sent mail urging them to give j\ntheir laundry to the only \"union\nshop\u201d in the Bronx.\nCanvassers visit these workers tell\ning them that this is a union shop.\nAs a matter of fact not even all the\ndrivers belong to the union, but the\ndrivers are only one-fifth of the\nworkers in the laundry. There are\nabout 50 workers there, mostly Negro\nwomen workers who get from sl2 to\nsl4 a week. This the A. F. L. calls\na union shop. This is the method of\norganizing the A. F. L. uses.\nTOey promise the boss more busi\nness for an agreement which leaves\nout four-fifths of the workers and\nwhich promises the boss \u201cnot to help*!\nor to influence the organization of\nthe inside workers.\u201d\nAll workers should be warned\nagainst the laundry racket of the A.\nF. L. and the bosses. The only or\nganization which organizes all the\nworkers into one union regardless of\ncraft or race is the Laundry Work\ners\u2019 League, 16 W. 21st St., affiliated\nto the Trade Union Unity League.\nLabor and Fraternal\nA I.ecfure Will Be Often\nBy Womens Council at 61 Jackson\nAve.. Bronx. Friday. Dec. 5. 7 p. m.\nSubject\u2014Womens Education to be\ndelivered by Comrade T. Gittinsky.\nBrinsr shopmates a lons\u2019\n\nThe llejriilnr Merlins;\nOs the Workers Bn bora tory Theatre\nTheatre of the W.I.R. will be every\nMonday. Wednesday and Friday eve\nnings at 8 p. m. at 1.11 W. 28th St.\n\nPrintline Worker* Industrial Leneiio\nMeeting of eoncentration group\nwill take plaee Thursday. Dec. 4. at\n6.30 p. m.. 16 W. 21st St.\nAll bindery workers in she TWIG\nmust come down Thursdav. Dec. 4.\n7.30 p. m. at 16 W. 21st St. Bring\nbindery worker contacts.\n\nImportant Emotion Meeting\nOs the Food Workers Industrial\nUnion Thursday. Dec. 4. at Tarty\nheadquarters. Important matters.\n\nAttention. Jersey City\n.V weekly study rlass in the funda*\nmenals of Communism has been ar\nranged every Friday night at 8:15\np. m. at the Workers Center. 337\nHenderson St. Fees are $2 for one\ncourse (12 lessons). Unemployed\nworkers free.\n\nSolidarity Hinof\nOs Coney Island Branch of the\ni League of Struggle of Negro Rights\nat 2901 Mermaid Avp.. Coney Tsln.nd.\nThursday. Dec. 4. 1930 at 8 p. ni. Ja*z\nband, admission free! All workers\ninvited.\n\nCirnnd Unit\nUnder the auspices of the Friends\nof the \u201cII Gavatore\u2019 for the benefit\nof the Italian orgaYi of the C.P.. Sat\nurday. Dec. 13. 8 p. m. at the Italian\nWorkers\u2019 Center. 2011 Third Ave.\nthet. 110th and 111th St Good music,\nfine program, contribution. 35 cents.\n\nAnl-Fn*cl\u00bb* Hall\nEntertainment and dance given by\nthe Bronx Branch Anti-Fascist Alli\nance of North America. .Satu/day. Dec.\n6. 8 p. m. at 569 Prospect Ave. Good\nmusic. Admission 35 cents.\n\nWOMEN'S DELEGATION OF THE\nR.I.L.U. TO SPEAK AT MA9B MEET\nSaturday. Dec. 4. at Irving Plaza.\nSpeakers will Include Wnv Z. Foster.\nSophie Melvin, textile worker; Anna\nKornblath. textile worker, and C. Me-\nLane, Negro needle trades worker.\n\nNeedle lYnilen Rail. December 5\nFriday, at Manhattan Lyceum, 66\nEast Fourth St. Good program. Tick\nets 50 cents. Can be secured at the\nUnion Headquarters. 131 W. 28th St.\nor the Morning Freiheit. DO E. 3th\nSt.\n\nProtest eMeting for the Ilelease of\nEileen Holme* and Mabel Husa\nWill be held Deo. 5 at the Finnish\nCooperative Hall. 5 E. 126th St. All\nyouth organizations and clubs ars\nurged to send delegate# to draft a\nresolution of protest.\n\nUnemployed Council*\nOs Hungarian. Checkoslovnk. Ger\nman workers will meet Thursday.\nDec. 11. 8 p. m. at 347 E. 72nd Ht..\nroom 7. At this meeting we will\nform the Yorkville Unemployed Coun\ncil.\n\nBuilding Maintenance Worker# Union\nGeneral membership meeting will\nbe held Wednesday. Dec. 3 at the\nGabor Tmple. 243 E. 84th St.\nmade to put It before the worglng\nclass. It should be sold at meetings\nand factory gates. \u201cSpeeding Up the\n1 Workers\u201d sells for 10 cents, with dls\n-1 counts on bundle*. Orders should be\nrushed to International Pamphlets,\n799 Broadway, New York, who will\nalso be glad to give Information con\ncernlng other important pamphlets\npublished by them. I\nDAILY WORKER, NEW YORK, TUESDAY, DECEMBER 2. 1930\nEAGLE PENCIL\nWORKERS STRIKE\nElect Their Committee;\nMass Picket Today\n(Continued from Page One)\nof the committee in to present de\nmands for a return of the\u2018wage cut\nto Richards, the big boss. Richards\nrefused to see the committee, and\nthe police drove the strikers, still j\nonly slightly organized for their task, j\nfrom the vicinity.\nFurther Organization.\nThe strikers then held another j\nmass meeting, larger than the first, J\nin Labor Temple and continued their\norganization, heard advice from the j\norganizer of the Trade Union Unity j\nCouncil, Jack Johnstone, and ar-}\nranged for mass picketing today\nwhen the shop opens. The decision j\nis for all strikers to meet at 7:30 a\nblock from the plant, and to picket\nit all around. After mass picketing\nin the morning, thfe strikers will meet\nagain in Labor Temple, and make up i\nthe shifts of 40 or so which will\nmaintain the picket lines between\nmass picketings. The strime commit-\ntee will again call upon the man-\nagement today.\nReject Wage Cut.\nThe ten per cent cut has been\nthreatened for some time. Deter- i\nmined refusal to accept it when it\nwas announced some weeks ago in\nseveral departments resulted in its\npostponement. The management tried I\nto spread a feeling of despair and j\nterror among the workers, and\nthought it could go ahead with the\ncut yesterday.\nThe workers were unorganized, ex\ncept for a factory committee, which\nissued a leaflet calling for strike yes\nterday unless the wage cut were\nrescinded. The plan, carried out very j\nsuccessfully, was for all to report to j\nwork, but not to work. If the wage j\ncut were not stopped by the company j\nat ten a. m. all were to come out and\nmarch in a body to the meeting\nplace.\nThe company fired one worker as I\nsoon as the call to refuse to work\nbegan to be circulated around the\nvarious departments. Later, at the\nstrike mass meeting, the strikers I\nshowed what they thought of this by\nelecting that worker chairman of the\nmeeting, and placing him on the\nstrike committee.\nAbout ten, groups of workers\nmarched out. A little later the doors\nof the plant were closed to try and\nsplit the workers and keep some of\nthem in. It did not work. The doors\nfinally had to be opened, when the\ncrowd of workers standing idle inside\nwere seen and urged by those out\nside to come on. They did. Later,\nas the march to the Labor Temple\nbegan, still another group marched\nout.\nThe factory police tried to propa\ngandize the workers against the\nstrike, saying, \"It will get you noth\ning.\u201d One woman worker showed\nthe cop her work hardened hands,\nand shouted, \u201cI\u2019ve been working here\nfor years and starving, now I'll try\nstriking.\u201d\nDiscuss Demands.\nThe first meeting was addressed\nby the representatives of the fac\ntory committee, and by Andrew Over\ngaard, national secretary of the\nMetal Workers' Industrial League of\nthe Trade Union Unity League, who\nsuggested the large strike committee\nand offered all possible help, but em\nphasized that this is the Eagle\nworkers\u2019 strike and their own soli\ndarity and organization would win it.\nMembers of the elected strike com\nmittee also spoke, and all the strti'\u2014s\nstarted for the factory to see the\ncommittee present the demands.\nAt the second meeting, held at 1:30\np. m., the strikers discussed the sit\nuation, many speaking from the\nfloor on tactics to follow and de\nmands to make. It was decided\nunanimously not to go back if the\nboss offers merely to make it a' lesser\nwage cut than ten per cent. The\ngreatest enthusiasm and cheers\ngreeted those who declared, \u201cWe\nwon\u2019t stand for any wage cut at alll\u201d\nIt was decided that if the manage\nment tries a lay-off after the strike\nis won, the committee shall demand\ninstead a reduction from the present\nnine hour day to the eight hour day\nand five day week, without reduc\ntion in the week\u2019s wages.\nA collection was taken up to de-\nSoviet Press Qives Workers\u2019\nAnswer to Boss War Plotters\n(Special Cable to the Daily Worker)\nMOSCOW, Dec. I.\u2014During the ex\namination of the chief prisoners\nRamsin, Larichev and Kalinikov, a\nnightmare picture of the military\ndictatorship to be set up in Russia\nafter the victory of the intervention\nist troops was shown.\nThe role of the French imperialists\nwas made especially clera in these\nplans. On this Pravda writes:\n\u201cThe bloody revenge of the Czarist\nwhite guards against the revolution\nary workers and peasants sales in\ncomparison with the exploits of the\nFrench General Staff, the Legion\nairs and the vassals in the colonies\nand in the countries they have occu-\nNew Alloy Discovered In U. S. S. R.\nMOSCOW, U. S. S. R.\u2014A new su\nper hard alloy has been developed by\na group of engineers at Baku, Soviet\noil center. It is many times cheaper\nand harder than foreign alloys.\nThose parts of machinery, like gears,\nexposed to great friction, and other\nnumerous types of instruments will\nbe covered with a layer of this alloy\nmaking possible a greater duration\n>0 PEP CENT CUT\nAT FALL RIVER\nCoupled With Police\nAttack on Union\nFALL RIVER, Mass., Dec. I.\u2014The\nmanagement of the Chase Mills, em\nploying about 300 workers here an\nnounced on Nov. 25 a wage cut for\nweavers of about 20 per cent to be\ncome operative today.\nThis wage vut was first proposed\nsix weeks ago but ownig to the mili\ntancy of the workers the bosses took\nthe advice of the United Textile\nWorkers officials and deferred action.\nSince that date victimization has been\nthe order of the day and the bosses\nnow consider the way clear for wage\ncutting.\nAt the same time police of Fall\nRiver are carrying on a drive aaginst\nthe National Textile Workers Uion,\nby every means they know of. They\nhave constantly demonstrated their\nforce at the mass meetings and have\nconvicted one of the N.T.W. members\non a frame-up charge of \u201creceiving\nstolen goods.\u201d They have also evicted\nthe U.T W. from tis headquarters.\nNevertheless the National Textile\nWorkers Union will organize the\nworkers of Chase and other mills.\nThe wage cut rouses opposition.\nfray expenses of the hall, the strike\ncommittee was charged to take up\nthe task of obtaining finances, get\nting relief, and telling the world that\nEagle Pencil is on strike against a\nten per cent wage cut and nobody\nshould try to take their jobs.\nGreat cheers greeted the announce\nment that the Councils of the Un\nemployed had recognized the strike\nand pledged not only to keep all job\nless workers from scabbing, but would\nprobably offer to help in picketing\nif required.\nFOR SALE\u2014Three rooms furniture,\nrecently purchased\u2014sacrifice. Call\nALG. 7956 for appointment.\nFo? h U'bml M\"nl ami I\u2019rnlHririan\nI'rloow K.\u00abt m t fli\u00ab\nUNIVERSAL CAFETERIA\nCop. 11th St. and University Place\n(Special Room for Conference*)\n___^\nEAT THE BEST AT THE\nHONEY DEW CAFETERIA\nIncorporated\nFourth Ave., Cor. 18th Street\nHOME-MADE .MEALS\nYou can Nelect the best foods, as we\nhave a great variety.\nW# are sure yoo will like our cooking\nHONEY DEW CAFETERIA\n4til Art., Cor. titli St.. New York City\nIncorporatwi\npied or seized like bandits.\n\u201cIn \u2018the best style\u2019 of those who\ninspired them, the counter-rgvolu\ntionary wreckers had drawn up an\nextensive program to \u2018calm down\u2019\nSoviet towns and villages. In the\ntestimony at court they were com\npelled to admit that they had pre\nared the fiercest bloody repression\nfor the proletariat and punitive ex\npeditions for millions of poor and\nmiddle peasants.\u201d\nWhile French, British and other\nimperialist papers, to conceal their\ncomplicity exposed in the trial, are\nfilled with fantastic legends of mut\ninies n cities and villages of the\n(Continued on Page Three)\nI of such parts and a consequent sav\ning of millions of roubles.\nThe engineers who discovered this\nnew formula, have named the alloy\n\"Stalinite\u201d to symbolize Stalin's firm\nness and strength. The enthusiasm\nof workers throughout the Soviet\nUnion has been noted through the\nmany inventions and improvements\ni on old inventions turned in.\nTWO JOBLESS WORKERS\nTAKE THEIR OWN LIVES\n9\nTwo more jobless workers, utterly\nwithout hope of getting jobs through\nfake government agencies, and not\nrealizing that running away from the\nstruggle against the bosses is ex\nactly what the latter want workers\nto do, have committed suicide.\nOne, Oscar Knight, 3333 Harrison\nAve., New York, slashed his throat\nand Wrists. The other, John Good,\nwas found hanging from a rafter in\nan abandoned garage in Warren,\nMich. Good had been out of work\nfor a year, Knight for several weeks.\nDEMAND RELEASE HUSA\nAND HOLMES.\nNEW YORK.\u2014AII workers, young\nand old. are urged to come to the\nmass meeting to be held this Friday.\n8 p. m\u201e at the Finnish Hall at 15 W.\n126t1i St., to demand the release oi\nMabel Husa and Eileen Holmes, held\nin Monroe County jail on a trumped\nup charge.\nB AMERICAN I\u2019REMIERE! I\nolutionary! Gristing!\nTHE BREAK-UP)\nire in tlx- tmtlltlon or Tot.mkin* IMnil Mali\ntoxtapliy Sovk-t Glim XI K lit .rrnr. p-irtto- I\nlomloiihly effective.\u201d\u2014Vern Smith. Dully Worker. 1\nOF THE OCTOBER REVOLUTION j\nBY MK.IKAISI'OIII.M in t.S.S.K I\nIT. PLAYHOUSE\nST., lielupoll I irili llml Ninth Atrs.\u2014Sprin* 8095 I\nI\u2019KICES\u2014CO.M\u2019IM OI 3 NOON TO MIDNIGHT\nTheatre Guild rrodurtlnn.\nELIZABETH,\nTHE QUEEN\nfljlin w. Otd. Et*. 8:40\nUUILU Mat*. Tli.ASnt. 2:40\nROAR CHINA\nMARTIN BECK\n46th St.\nWent of Brondwny\nCv*. 8:50. Mts. Th. A tin t. 2:60\nMUSIC AND CONCERTS\nCARNEGIE IIALL, Irll. Kv., Dec. 6, S:SO J\nLevitzki\n,M\u00abt. NBC Artist* Service (Stelnnaj) I\nWOECORRS MEET\nSTARTSCONTEST\nCity Groups Worcorrs\nPrimary Aim\nNEW YORK.\u2014New York and\nvicinity worker correspondents gath\nered Sunday, Nov. 30, at 2 p. -m. at!\ntheir second monthly meeting.\nFollowing the report of the secre\ntary of the Worker Correspondents j\nLeague (Worcorrs) a full discussion\nwas held, in which all present par\nticipated.\nDruker, secretary, pointed out that\nthe League is building and maintain\ning connections with hundreds of\nworker correspondents and laying the\nbasis for the building of city Wor\ncorrs groups in all parts of the coun\ntry. A monthly bulletin is issued by\nthe Worcorrs League and 300 of the\nlast three issues have been mailed\nout. A contest for the best city corre\nspondence was approved.\nAdditions were made to the execu\ntive committee by the election of new\nmembers. All worker correspondents\nwishing information or the Worcorrs\nBulletin should write to Worcorrs, 50\nE. 13th St., New York.\nHATHAWAY TO SPEAK ON\nFOR WAR\u201d\nNEW YORK.\u2014Five hundred work\ners filled Irving Plaza on Sunday,\nNov. 30, to hear Max Bedacht speak\non the \u201cCrisis of Capitalism.\u201d\nThe workers started to come as\nearly as 6:30, so that by 8 o\u2019clock\nthe hall was quite crowded. The\nworkers kept coming until 9:30.\nThey listened attentively to the lec\nture. That was quite evident by the\nnumber of varied questions asked.\nOn Sunday. Dec. 7, C .A. Hathaway,\neditor of the Daily Worker, will speak\non \u201cDisarming for War.\u201d\nThis subject should interest all the\nworkers to come and hear why the\ncapitalist countries are talking\n\u201cpeace\" and arming for war.\nKNIT GOODS JOBLESS MEET\nNEW YORK.\u2014AII jobless knit\nj goods workers arc invited to the\nI regular Tuesday morning meeting of\nj the Unemployed Council in their\nI trade. The meeting today is at 10\nla. m\u201e at 131 West 28th St.\nCivic repertory u \u00abu> a,-.\nEvening. 9:30\nS 'o. *l. *I.BO. Mule. Th. Sul. 230\nEVA LE GALIIKNNK, Director\nNIEGIRIED\nTom. Nixht ALISON\u2019S HOUSE\nSeats4wk\u00bb.a<lv.ntHtnOrf.&T'nHall,imv.43\nNINA ROSA\nNew Musical Ituinance, with\nGt V ROBERTSON. KTHKLINO TERRI\nAKMIDA, LEONARD CEELEY, other.\nMAJESTIC THEA., 44th. W. r\u00bbf Brandtra,\nKv*. H:\u00bb9, Mat*. Wed. Si Nat. 2:30. Clll. 2900\nTHE GREEKS HAD\nA WORD FOR H\nA COMEDY BY ZOK AKINS\nHAM H. HARRIS The*.. 4td St. W. at B\u2019\u00bb\nI Eventac SiBO. Mata. Wad. Sat. t:SO\n1 I _ _. _.\nArteff Theatre\nTroupe to Attend\nNeedle Trade Ball\nNEW YORK.\u2014New York workers\nwill have an opportunity to acquaint\nthemselves with the whole Artef\nTheatre group at the ball of the\nNeedle Trades Workers Industrial\nUnion, on Friday evening, Decem\nber sth. The ball will be held in\nManhattan Lyceum. 66 East 4th St.,\nand will be one of the biggest held\nthis season.\nThe Artef troupe will come right\nafter their playing in the theatre in\ntheir new hat \"BrilUanten.\u201d They\nwill not change their costumes. Many\nother organizations have promised to\nbring their members to this ball and\nhelp make it a success.\nNo sympathetic Workers\u2019 organi\nzation will have an affair on Friday\nDecember sth. Many other organiza\ntions have postponed their own af\nfairs for a later date.\nThis ball will be a demonstration\nof solidarity with the needle trade\nworkers in iproof of readiness of\nthese organizations to help in\ncoming dress strike. Friends of the\nrevolutionary unions will meet this\ntime at the Needle Trades ball, next\ntime on the picket, line.\nLet no worker miss this affair. Ask\nyour friends whether they have al\nready their tickets for the Needle\nTrade Ball, if not tickets can be\nbought at the office of the union, 131\nWest 28th Street, or in the office of\nthe Morning Freiheit. 50 East 13th\nStreet. The price of admission is\ndnly 50 cents.\n\u201cFor AU Kinds of Insurance\nf ARL BRODSKV\nTelephone: Oftirrav Rill r.x.M A\n7 East 42nd Street, New York\nCooperators I Patronise\nSEROY\nCHEMIST\n657 Allerton Avenue\nEsfabrook 3215 Bronx, N Y\n**^T\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 a\n\nDEWEY 9914 Office Hours:\n9 A. M.-9 P. M.\nSunday: 10 A. M.-l P M.\nDR. J. LEVIN\nSURGEON DENTIST\nISO I AVENUE U Are. U Sta., B.M.T.\nAt East 15th St. BROOKLYN, J\u00bb. T.\nDR. J. MINDEL\nSUKOEI N DENTIST\nI UNION SQUARE\nKtom *o3 Phone: Algonquin till\nSot eovnected urith any\nother office\nMELROSE^\nn-vlrw *km*'*\u00bbhia*\nLsairy kishmhvt\npom mile. Will Alive?. Find It\nWr I'lenaitnf 40 titne at Out Pine*.\n1787 SOUTHERN Bl.Vb, Bronx\n(near I7\u00abch Ht. station)\nPHONE:\u2014 INTEKV ALB tl it.\nRATIONAL\nVegetarian\nRESTAURANT\n199 SECOND ATE, UE\nBat. Itth and 13th Sts.\nStrictly Vegetarian Food\nHEALTH FOOD\nVegetarian\nRESTAURANT\n1600 MADISON AVE\nPhone: UNlversilj 586 S\n\u2014\u2014J\n\u201chone: Sturveeant Silt\nJohn\u2019s Restaurant\nSPEUIAI.Tft ITA 1,1 A V IIISHES\nA pince with ntmnapheha\nwhere all radical* meat\n302 K. 12th St. New York\nAdvertise yw Union Meeting*\nhere. For information i orite to\nThe DAILY WORKER\nAdverttelnir Dept\n80 East 13th St. Naw York CKft\n\u2014ii. nd","height":"26125","width":"20350"}}
